data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, new built-in `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>`. Expression trees **cannot represent span-based methods**, so it fails at runtime.

## How to fix it

Force the call to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or using `.AsEnumerable()`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `Enumerable.Reverse` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` extension). The general fix pattern is the same: disambiguate with `.AsEnumerable()`, a cast to `IEnumerable<T>`, or an explicit `Enumerable.Method(...)` call.
